.SH "Typedef Documentation"
.PP 
.SS "typedef struct \fB__cstring\fP \fBCSTRING\fP"
\fBcstring\&.h\fP : c string library to make Ron happy\&. Wrapper around plain C strings that handles automatically growing the string as data is concattenated to the end\&. (note: this is an improved version of cstring from supermon\&. Migrate it into that library eventually\&.\&.\&. )

.PP
-matt sottile Structure wrapping the character pointer and size counters (allocated vs\&. actual used)\&. 
.SH "Function Documentation"
.PP 
.SS "\fBCSTRING\fP * sadd (\fBCSTRING\fP * s, char * a)"
Concatenate the second argument to the \fBCSTRING\fP passed in the first\&. The second argument must be a pointer to a null terminated string\&. A NULL return value indicates that something went wrong and that sexp_errno should be checked for the cause\&. The contents of s are left alone\&. As such, the caller should check the pointer returned before overwriting the value of s, as this may result in a memory leak if an error condition occurs\&. 
.SS "\fBCSTRING\fP * saddch (\fBCSTRING\fP * s, char a)"
Append a character to the end of the \fBCSTRING\fP\&. A NULL return value indicates that something went wrong and that sexp_errno should be checked for the cause\&. The contents of s are left alone\&. As such, the caller should check the pointer returned before overwriting the value of s, as this may result in a memory leak if an error condition occurs\&. 
.SS "void sdestroy (\fBCSTRING\fP * s)"
Destroy the \fBCSTRING\fP struct and the data it points at\&. 
.SS "void sempty (\fBCSTRING\fP * s)"
Set the current length to zero, effectively dumping the string without deallocating it so we can use it later without reallocating any memory\&. 
.SS "void sgrowsize (size_t s)"
Set the growth size\&. Values less than one are ignored\&. 
.SS "\fBCSTRING\fP * snew (size_t s)"
Allocate a new \fBCSTRING\fP of the given size\&. A NULL return value indicates that something went wrong and that sexp_errno should be checked for the cause\&. 
.SS "\fBCSTRING\fP * strim (\fBCSTRING\fP * s)"
Trim the allocated memory to precisely the string length plus one char to hold the null terminator A NULL return value indicates that something went wrong and that sexp_errno should be checked for the cause\&. The contents of s are left alone\&. As such, the caller should check the pointer returned before overwriting the value of s, as this may result in a memory leak if an error condition occurs\&. 
.SS "char * toCharPtr (\fBCSTRING\fP * s)"
Return the base pointer of the \fBCSTRING\fP\&. NULL either means the base pointer was null, or the \fBCSTRING\fP itself was NULL\&. 
